text_Obsidian: Obsidian is a very shiny deep black.  There can be other colors but most of the rock is a deep, shiny black.
text_Pegmatite: Has a lot of white. IT can have other colors mixed in but is primarily a lighter rock. Can have greens, blacks, orange along the lighter color.

text_Basalt: Basalt is a darker stone.  It can have some additional color but is a dull, dark stone.
text_Peridotite: Peridotite tends to appear very green but can also have lighter or darker stone with it.  The main characteristic seems to be the green color.

text_Andesite: Andesite is a black to grey rock that has lighter colors sprinkled in
text_Diorite: Diorite is a lighter rock with darker colors mixed in, often looks spotted with the darker colors.

text_Pegmatite: Colors often seem to be in more random spots, like there isn't really a pattern (no lines, etc).  Tends to have very contrasting colors.
text_Peridotite: Usually has a green tint.  Often there are distinct spots or lines.

text_Basalt: Basalt tends to be a dark black and more square/rectangular.  It is a deep but dull black.
text_Gabbro: Gabbro also tends to have a deep dull black but has other colors mixed in more prominently.  There is more of a contrast between colors.

text_Diorite: Diorite is a lighter stone with contrasting colors sprinkled in.  The colors are often dots or look like moss/mold
text_Gabbro: Gabbro is a dark dull blackish color and can have more subtle colors mixed in.
